10 Sec. 718. From the funds appropriated in part 1, the
11 department must pursue all opportunities to reduce costs for
12 prisoners and prisoners' families for financial deposit fees and
13 commissary fees when the department negotiates or renews any
14 contract to provide these services.
15 Sec. 719. (1) Funds appropriated in part 1 for contraband
16 prevention must be used by the department to enhance a multifaceted
17 approach to contraband prevention that combines technology,
18 rigorous policies, vigilant staff, intelligence gathering, and a
19 commitment to addressing the root causes of contraband, all of
20 which are necessary for preventing contraband introductions and
21 maintaining safe and secure correctional facilities.
22 (2) Funds appropriated in part 1 for contraband prevention
23 must be used by the department to support the prevention of
24 contraband in correctional facilities, including increasing the
25 frequency and enhancing the methods of screening all individuals,
26 including all department employees, and all items entering into
27 correctional facilities.
28 (3) From the funds appropriated in part 1 for contraband
29 prevention, the department must submit a report not later than
ERE S06102'26 (S-1) 9n6epi

101
1 March 1 on contraband and prevention efforts in correctional
2 facilities. The report must include, but not be limited to, all of
3 the following:
4 (a) Prevention efforts and strategies utilized by the
5 department.
6 (b) Challenges faced by correctional staff and other staff in
7 addressing contraband.
8 (c) Ideas and recommendations on how the legislature can
9 better assist the department with contraband prevention efforts and
10 strategies.
11 Sec. 720. The department shall ensure that Policy Directive
12 04.01.110 "Access to Correctional Facilities" does not require
13 active legislative members in good standing to provide prior notice
14 before being granted access to a department facility when
15 conducting official legislative business.
16 Sec. 721. It is the intent of the legislature that the
17 department shall adopt a policy where strip searches are based on
18 suspicion or are randomized so that it results in fewer and less
19 intrusive strip searches of prisoners to maintain the safety and
20 security of correctional facilities. If the department undertakes
21 any efforts to perform fewer and less invasive strip searches, it
22 must provide a report by April 1 on the efforts undertaken.
23 Sec. 723. From the funds appropriated in part 1, the
24 department must allow a prisoner at least 1 in-person visit per 6-
25 month period, regardless of the prisoner's violation status,
26 including a prisoner who is on restricted visitation due to
27 substance use. A prisoner is excluded from the 1 in-person visit
28 requirement if the prisoner is on restricted visitation for
29 violence against other prisoners or violence against any department
ERE S06102'26 (S-1) 9n6epi

102
1 staff. In addition, the department must do all of the following
2 regarding the visits required under this section:
3 (a) Prioritize providing staggered time frames for visitors to
4 sign up for open visiting slots.
5 (b) Review department protocol for restricting prisoner
6 visitation, including, but not limited to, Policy Directive 05-03-
7 140, with the intent of reforming the protocol so that fewer
8 prisoners with substance use misconducts have their visits
9 restricted.
10 (c) Ensure visitation areas are child-friendly by providing
11 toys, puzzles, and other child-friendly games and activities.
12 (d) Prioritize providing healthy food choices in vending
13 machines located in visitation areas of correctional facilities,
14 including fruits, vegetables, and food items made with whole
15 ingredients.
16 (e) Provide a report, by April 1, detailing the efforts taken
17 to meet the requirements of subdivisions (a) to (d) and the
18 outcomes of these changes and effects on visitation privileges for
19 prisoners.
20 Sec. 724. From the funds appropriated in part 1, the
21 department must provide a report by April 1 for the Women's Huron
22 Valley Correctional Complex that details the meals and medication
23 administration missed by prisoners at the complex due to lack of
24 wheelchair access. The report must include all of the following
25 information:
26 (a) The total number of meals missed by prisoners due to lack
27 of wheelchair access.
28 (b) The total number of prisoners who were not administered
29 prescribed medication according to their electronic medication
ERE S06102'26 (S-1) 9n6epi

103
1 administration record due to a lack of wheelchair access.
2 Sec. 725. From the funds appropriated in part 1, the
3 department must provide a report, by facility, by April 1 on the
4 prisoner benefit fund. The report must include, for each facility,
5 all of the following information:
6 (a) The balance of the fund as of September 30 of the previous
7 fiscal year.
8 (b) The total amount deposited into the fund in the previous
9 fiscal year, categorized by the source of deposit.
10 (c) The total amount spent from the fund in the previous
11 fiscal year.
12 (d) The general categories of the expenditure of the funds and
13 the amounts spent by category.
14 Sec. 726. It is the intent of the legislature that, in the
15 event corrections officers at a state correctional facility express
16 interest in transitioning to a 12-hour shift schedule, the
17 recognized collective bargaining representative shall conduct a
18 vote to determine such interest. If the majority of voting
19 corrections officers approve the proposed schedule, the department
20 shall implement a 12-hour shift schedule at that correctional
21 facility.
