4 affordability, the department shall allocate $10,000,000.00 as
5 grants to qualified providers to assist eligible residents who have
6 a financial burden, have accumulated a balance on their water
7 utility bill, have had their water service shut off, and/or are at
8 risk of having their water service shut off. Eligible expenditures
9 from these funds must be income-based and must include all of the
10 following:
11 (a) Restoring residential water service.
12 (b) Paying down water bills currently in arrears.
13 (c) Supporting reasonable water affordability plans that are
14 based on an individual's ability to pay, including capped payments
15 based on household income to prevent accumulating a balance on
16 future water bills and funding to qualified providers to cover the
17 remaining cost of service.
18 (d) Protecting participating residents from water shutoffs.
19 (2) To be considered a qualified provider under this section,
20 the provider must be 1 of the following:
21 (a) A community water system.
22 (b) A community action agency.
23 (c) A nonprofit, community-based organization organized under
24 the laws of this state that is exempt from federal income tax under
25 section 501(c)(3) of the internal revenue code of 1986, 26 USC 501,
26 with a history of doing utility assistance work.
27 (3) Qualified providers receiving grants under this section
28 may spend not more than 3% of the total grant award for
29 administrative services related to the implementation of this
ERE S06102'26 (S-1) 9n6epi

512
1 section.
2 (4) Qualified providers receiving grants under this section
3 shall report to the department by September 30 of the current
4 fiscal year on outcomes and performance measures for the program,
5 including, but not limited to, all of the following:
6 (a) The total grant award received by the qualified provider.
7 (b) The percentage of the grant award that was used for
8 administrative costs.
9 (c) The total dollars spent broken down by type of assistance
10 provided.
11 (d) The number of individuals helped broken down by type of
12 assistance provided.
13 (e) The number of individual applicants denied assistance.
14 (5) Upon receipt of the information required under subsection
15 (4), the department shall compile and forward the report to the
16 standard report recipients.
17 (6) The unexpended funds appropriated in part 1 for water
18 affordability are designated as a work project appropriation, and
19 any unencumbered or unallotted funds shall not lapse at the end of
20 the fiscal year and shall be available for expenditures for
21 projects under this section until the projects have been completed.
22 The following is in compliance with section 451a of the management
23 and budget act, 1984 PA 431, MCL 18.1451a:
24 (a) The purpose of the project is to provide grants to
25 qualified providers that assist eligible residents who have a
26 financial burden, have accumulated a balance on their water utility
27 bill, have had their water service shut off, and/or are at risk of
28 having their water service shut off.
29 (b) The project will be accomplished through competitive
ERE S06102'26 (S-1) 9n6epi

513
1 grants to qualified providers.
2 (c) The total estimated cost of the project is $10,000,000.00.
3 (d) The tentative completion date is September 30, 2031.
