1 Sec. 1005. (1) The funds appropriated in part 1 for talent
2 partnership must be used to administer a grant program to support
3 implementation of transformational community development
4 initiatives.
5 (2) Talent partnership grant funding must be used to implement
6 transformational public space development projects in central city
7 neighborhoods or concentrated districts and leverage
8 interdepartmental and cross-sector coordination through local
9 talent plans that are designed to increase this state's population
10 of young talent by creating high-density, high-amenity, walkable,
11 vibrant-street-life neighborhoods or districts and to create
12 business ownership opportunities for local residents. Qualified
13 plan proposals must include all of the following:
14 (a) The transition of roadway usage from cars to alternative
15 transportation spaces, including, but not limited to, walking,
16 biking, and transit.
17 (b) Commercial corridor activation, including innovations to
18 fill vacant retail space with locally owned businesses.
19 (c) Mixed-use development that contributes to dense, walkable
20 areas.
21 (d) A plan to do all of the following:
22 (i) Support greater density.
23 (ii) Increase access to affordable or middle-income housing.
24 (iii) Improve direct access to multimodal transportation.
25 (iv) Improve quality of life through increased parks, green
26 spaces, outdoor recreation, and arts and cultural amenities.
27 (3) The legislature finds and declares that the appropriation
28 described in this section is for a public purpose and serves the
29 health, safety, and general welfare of the residents of this state.
ERE S06102'26 (S-1) 9n6epi

647
1 (4) The department may do any of the following to implement
2 the grant program:
3 (a) Develop guidelines to accept and review local talent plans
4 from eligible applicants and award funding for approved local
5 talent plans to increase this state's population of young talent by
6 creating high-density, high-amenity, walkable, vibrant-street-life
7 neighborhoods or districts and to create business ownership
8 opportunities for local residents.
9 (b) Consult with local stakeholders, provide education and
10 consultation to the public during the application process, and
